            <article class="post-76241 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-data-source category-economics" id="post-76241">
  <header class="entry-header">

          <h2 class="entry-title"><a href="https://marginalrevolution.com/marginalrevolution/2019/06/people-like-working-with-their-friends-but-it-makes-them-less-productive.html">People like working with their friends, but it makes them less productive</a></h2>
    
      <div class="byline">
        by&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="author"><a href="/about">Tyler Cowen</a></span>
        <time class="entry-date published" datetime="2019-06-29 02:35:01">June 29, 2019 at 2:35 am </time>
                            in
          <ul class="entry-tags">
                                        <li class="tag" rel="tag"><a href="https://marginalrevolution.com/marginalrevolution/category/data-source">Data Source</a></li>
                                                      <li class="tag" rel="tag"><a href="https://marginalrevolution.com/marginalrevolution/category/economics">Economics</a></li>
                                    </ul><!-- /.entry-tags -->
                        </div><!-- /.byline -->
  </header><!-- /.entry-header -->
  <div class="entry-content">
    <div class="pf-content"><p>From Sangyoon Park:</p>
<blockquote><p>Through a field experiment at a seafood-processing plant, I examine how working alongside friends affects employee productivity and how this effect is heterogeneous with respect to an employee&#8217;s personality. This paper presents two main findings. First, worker productivity declines when a friend is close enough to socialize with. Second, workers who are higher on the conscientiousness scale show smaller productivity declines when working alongside a friend. Estimates suggest that a median worker is willing to pay 4.5 percent of her wage to work next to friends.</p></blockquote>
<p>That is <a href="https://www.aeaweb.org/articles?id=10.1257/app.20160650&amp;&amp;from=f" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">from American Economic Journal: Applied Economics</a>, via Adam Ozimek.</p>
</div>
  </div><!-- /.entry-content -->
  <footer class="entry-footer">

    <section class="post-actions">
